Got BDE?‚ö°Ô∏è
New YouTube vid HERE [ https://substack.com/redirect/1746b581-c193-4b0a-851d-9880b27b2aa4?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]üîó all about SQL!!!!
Quiet quitting your corporate job is out. It‚Äôs soooooo summer 2022.
In 2025, quiet cracking is IN. And 54% of people are experiencing it. Read the full Business Insider article here üîó [ https://substack.com/redirect/1d4f0ee9-ee90-41ab-99db-679bf58a0fcb?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]. 
What is quiet cracking?
It‚Äôs the latest new trend to represent how people are coping with (or not coping with‚Ä¶) the state of the job market and workforce. The job market is shit. The workforce is also shit for a lot of people, and people are feeling stuck but scared to take action.
Quiet cracking is silently falling apart at work... So these people show up and do their job, but they're just struggling in silence and slowly dying on the inside. These aren‚Äôt people who are openly and obviously burnt out or quiet quitting, they‚Äôre people you probably don‚Äôt even expect.
Suffering in Silence‚Ä¶
Managers and coworkers usually can‚Äôt even see the signs because the quiet cracker (yes I made up this noun version of the term) is hiding it to suffer in silence. They don‚Äôt want the attention on them or any kind of conflict. Especially if it could result in a worsened situation politically or even lead to being cut! The fear keeps them shackled.
Most employees who are quiet cracking are still performing somewhat well, so it's kind of hard to see the signs. But they might be having more headaches, more fatigue, and overall just loss of hope. They might even start making a few mistakes here and there due to the lack of engagement. We can't even blame people because work conditions are declining and the job market is in the gutter. People have bills to pay, so staying, suffering, and disassociating is the best thing for survival. I mean come on, we‚Äôve all been there, right??
The Cost:
It's not JUST about feelings and well-being. It's actually costing the global economy $438 billion in loss of productivity‚Äî the highest since COVID. It‚Äôs a really serious issue on a higher level that could impact the economy long term‚Ä¶ A lot of people are disassociating and producing less at work but not enough to be seen. They‚Äôre still flying under the radar. 
Aside from the fact that they‚Äôre unhappy and suffering, healthy work boundaries aren‚Äôt necessarily a bad thing. We‚Äôre all just here to pay our bills and survive at the end of the day.
If you‚Äôre quiet cracking now, I see you.

Lesson 18: Basic Date Functions
üé• Video [ https://substack.com/redirect/373099b5-c0b6-4ace-85ab-e25fda1000b4?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Dates can be one of the most annoying things to work with in data, but using basic date functions can help us extract and isolate different parts of the date to be used in filtering, creating new columns, and transforming our data. Here are the main date functions we can use to extract different parts of the date: 
month(): Extracts the month from a date.
day(): Extracts the day from a date.
year(): Extracts the year from a date.
We can also extract time parts from timestamps when applicable as well: 
hour(): Extracts the hour from a datetime or timestamp.
minute(): Extracts the minute from a datetime or timestamp.
second(): Extracts the second from a datetime or timestamp.
If there is no timestamp, and you input a regular date into a time function like these above, the result will be 0 since the default timestamp on a regular date data type is 00:00:00. 
This was an incredibly short lesson, but we have to start with the date basics, so we can get to the juicier stuff later on! üî•

Dear friends,

We‚Äôre organizing a new event called Buildathon: The Rapid Engineering Competition, to be held in the San Francisco Bay Area on Saturday, August 16, 2025! You can learn more and apply to participate here (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VVXZb24RhTN4W6dx1km3MnbTbW9ccHTJ5znPrVN4xH9d23prCCW69sMD-6lZ3ppW95WMD232vNqXW1SRhzk1bzK7cN2cptkrWdnkdW3h2G4991LZmxW87r5sq8fHhYzW4sCdGY3R1tgFVqfc1l1_2bH8W31xS5s4SD94pW44tsVJ8T4cfkW3-RG9Q2ppqKbW5RYxGD2CSt1FW2tbP1_17_MpzW5s9ZTc2SP2knW5LL62Z5_45vZW7kJfw52GjBzdVXctpK726RyHW6BNtpl7hn1yfW1lxY28853tY6W4YDVrk7qCMGnV6NDXN7l5CrPf4sFwFs04 ) .

AI-assisted coding is speeding up software engineering more than most people appreciate.  We‚Äôre inviting the best builders from Silicon Valley and around the world to compete in person on rapidly engineering software.

I‚Äôve observed a wide spectrum of AI adoption among software engineers. Some use AI only occasionally ‚Äî for example, asking LLMs basic coding questions. Others have integrated AI-assisted IDEs like Cursor or Windsurf into their daily work. More advanced users are skilled at directing agentic coding assistants such as Claude Code and Gemini CLI. A small but growing group is now orchestrating multiple AI agents working in parallel across different parts of a large codebase.

In tech, the desire to chase the latest shiny technology sometimes leads individuals and even businesses to switch tooling more often than necessary. But the rapid evolution of AI coding tools means teams that are half a generation behind can be significantly less productive than those at the bleeding edge.

Code autocompletion by GitHub Copilot was cutting-edge 2 years ago, but it‚Äôs nowhere near what is possible now! For example, my team AI Fund routinely goes from a product idea to a basic working product or prototype in hours. This is why overcoming the Product Management Bottleneck (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VVXZb24RhTN4W6dx1km3MnbTbW9ccHTJ5znPrVN4xH9fx3prCCW95jsWP6lZ3lLW1bJb866-RRZ5V3DPkd1MdRQ5W7Kz3vb5YspdDW3YDj_T17Z6mLW68XtvM8CHs_jW4YWM4l37fgvqW29B25H8HCDfnW1GYyXs3JN9trW7v_FnZ1CB47TW6ZFcmF5vgBTRW4xVYgH8yfzqqW3Gg92z5NnRSZW6CpYyH5G2rw6W47MzL16YLjhFW1x_XQm6prp4pW1bHHCD3w8P_mVgPS948vP-BhW2Yxgnh2x1qcsW6pfz148PrTWhW1qq8pt3N2RqXW3ZZRwb6Tzqm8W934kCF3vDWlDW3yZ30g4pN8qbW5CMLFN4rrPMwW2dbbWr8JP3dgW1LZ2cW7qdLNXW4k4h6T9bTVQTW7QwK3-237hYNW2RJ_kK4htt4WW4qZTr36gP-Fgf6frHdW04 ) ‚Äî deciding what to build rather than the actual building ‚Äî occupies a growing part of our effort.

DeepLearning.AI and AI Fund are organizing this Buildathon competition to see how quickly the best developers can build products. We‚Äôll provide a loose product spec, say on a Real-Time Multiplayer Code Editor or Personal Finance Tracker (see above). Historically, these products may have taken a team of 2 or 3 engineers weeks or months to build. But we hope participants will be able to build them in closer to 60 minutes. You can read more about the competition format here.

If you use AI-assisted coding to engineer software quickly, please join our Buildathon here (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VVXZb24RhTN4W6dx1km3MnbTbW9ccHTJ5znPrVN4xH9d23prCCW69sMD-6lZ3ppW95WMD232vNqXW1SRhzk1bzK7cN2cptkrWdnkdW3h2G4991LZmxW87r5sq8fHhYzW4sCdGY3R1tgFVqfc1l1_2bH8W31xS5s4SD94pW44tsVJ8T4cfkW3-RG9Q2ppqKbW5RYxGD2CSt1FW2tbP1_17_MpzW5s9ZTc2SP2knW5LL62Z5_45vZW7kJfw52GjBzdVXctpK726RyHW6BNtpl7hn1yfW1lxY28853tY6W4YDVrk7qCMGnV6NDXN7l5CrPf4sFwFs04 ) and show us your skills!

An agent‚Äôs performance depends not only on an effective workflow but also on a large language model that excels at agentic activities. A new open-weights model focuses on those capabilities.

What‚Äôs new: Beijing-based Moonshot AI released the Kimi K2 (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VVXZb24RhTN4W6dx1km3MnbTbW9ccHTJ5znPrVN4xH9dl3prCCW6N1vHY6lZ3kyW8n9dKv70RVh6W7KQjXg317KFhW93Ck1L8XNbHCN2PWJSpq9zqMW6nT1bv6146gFW99LRDz2hbpwfVMw5V95cXk-fW6Hl8zd2Gyk_4W919-4m5hQmd7W9bxd3R7YmN-yW43Fq_d8_R72ZW25Brpg6-Q8XZW5nMkL831R2kjW5f1dbX4jsfhWN7k4_L8fjkpqW7MCF6t89pcJsW6zlvKZ5b2Z6SW8ZrT298xvwprVf76Gh7pdbgwW81jkLj10VzpPW6ql3g191Kx0gVWvM447KRDlzdBPk7204 ) family of 1 trillion-parameter large language models (LLMs). - Input/output: Text in (up to around 128,000 tokens), text out (up to around 16,000 tokens)
- Architecture: Mixture-of-experts transformer, 1 trillion parameters total, 32 billion parameters active

How it works: Moonshot pretrained the models on 15.5 trillion tokens from undisclosed sources. It fine-tuned Kimi-K2-Instruct via reinforcement learning using a proprietary dataset.

- To enable Kimi-K2-Instruct to use tools, the team generated a large dataset of examples in which models used tools, both real-world and synthetic, that implement model context protocol (MCP (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VVXZb24RhTN4W6dx1km3MnbTbW9ccHTJ5znPrVN4xH9fd3prCCW8wLKSR6lZ3mrW2HbFFK2XvB3FW8gs_dK7mK2JLW3SWrWP8vcPvZW422wd57sn-vYV2yLKr7mG2slV5bJV938dl1qW113WHN5dRyYrW6xHFNn7zn7x4W5RZLVn2XXs0rW5m5HVN7X4QcGW4CwsSk6kjG1dW7x4dXB78XW66VDV0-_6s8GTdW2Z556S4VqztdW2mYP9D810N02N6nmPlMPVJhBN5DhrfHqpnnvW1K4Sl_4VcJDRW4kmGpH4gjcPyW1tYBgV4GCwsDW7_wPJ17STBwVW8kTphT4bHrb1N69NqrBQqSJgW4GcYBy5nYg0fW7cpKnd8jsq5vW1_gNJP1Wwl_mW73Q5Qm22-DhbW463mJ-6ZwG4Gf5VTvNl04 ) ). Unidentified models acted as users, and other unidentified models acted as agents that solved tasks assigned by the users.  A further model acted as a judge to filter out unsuccessful examples.
- The team fine-tuned Kimi-K2-Instruct via reinforcement learning. The model evaluated its own performance, used its evaluation as a reward, and iteratively improved its performance.
- The team also fine-tuned Kimi-K2-Instruct to solve coding and math problems via reinforcement learning. The model did not evaluate its own performance on these problems; it determined rewards according to pre-existing solutions or unit tests.

Results: Moonshot compared Kimi-K2-Instruct to two open-weights, non-reasoning models (DeepSeek-V3 and Qwen3-235B-A22B with reasoning switched off) and four closed, non-reasoning models.

- Kimi-K2-Instruct outperformed the open-weights models across a range of benchmarks for tool use, coding, math, reasoning, and general knowledge.
- It achieved middling performance relative to the closed models, though it did relatively well in math and science tasks.
- Compared to all models tested, on LiveCodeBench (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VVXZb24RhTN4W6dx1km3MnbTbW9ccHTJ5znPrVN4xH9dl3prCCW6N1vHY6lZ3m2W1tnkgn1fswd0W6H1mT21RGl9sVVbD7l85YQTxMCsK0WBNbWCW2Zkq9b1X6RjqW1hkw2L97ZKDfW480-3q8_tGfYW9cM3Zx5FTzNHVdkchk7Wkz29W4Ln2D12ZpzhpW6vCS5t8vs-fWW7mm3ns1qHxX5VPrvdj8-8YZTN5fx7G0j-D86W76RgGp7vzstyW4m7SZm3ffNkGW5JB6vG8MqS17W7lVZzy5mPFqkW7vbJL88rL4P5W6W2Ml64ttvCKW7MQk5-6SNsxsV9f70M1srhtvf4lCGdR04 )  (coding tasks), Kimi K2 (53 percent) achieved the best performance, ahead of Claude Sonnet 4 with extended thinking mode switched off (48.5 percent).
- Among all models tested, on AceBench (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VVXZb24RhTN4W6dx1km3MnbTbW9ccHTJ5znPrVN4xH9dl3prCCW6N1vHY6lZ3pVW2hKfvv742mFXW5C8SxY91Qx9kW4z7HYV3lQKnsN4mJ9rKC5VNWW7J3LLc7wBmmBW8VTpb-4vxTmmW5fl8vG5B6xZnV9vX3H5VlXb0W9hq48z5X4LZ8W99-JVJ4WR3X1N7YJzX0sBLF_W11nRBP67yHTRW1SlrJW15MMVyW47vJh43jKPR3W3jFbyf4MkbMBW4-4NMd2ct64YW8Tmh3t62H-j2W3V6nkh275f5yW5fKgG46LTlxkN7rvPmgs4tFHW4R6rnP7QTn-mW4g4LVr49kpsBf3WmCpP04 ) (tool use), Kimi K2 (76.5 percent accuracy) placed second behind GPT 4.1 (80.1 percent accuracy).
- On 8 out of 11 math and science benchmarks, Kimi K2 achieved the best performance of all models tested.

Why it matters: Demand is growing for LLMs that carry out agentic workflows accurately, as these workflows lead to better performance. Kimi-K2-Instruct gives developers a strong option for fine-tuning models for their own agentic tasks.

We‚Äôre thinking: Early LLMs were built to generate output for human consumption. But the rise of agentic workflows means that more and more LLM output is consumed by computers, so it makes good sense to put more research and training effort into building LLMs that generate output for computers. A leading LLM optimized for agentic workflows is a boon to developers!

How to Comply With the EU‚Äôs AI Act

The European Union published guidelines to help builders of AI models to comply with the AI Act, which wasenacted last year.

What‚Äôs new: The General Purpose AI Code of Practice (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VVXZb24RhTN4W6dx1km3MnbTbW9ccHTJ5znPrVN4xH9dY3prCCW7Y8-PT6lZ3n3VhxYd-6zr6BTW7DPX_q99fDLyW3cPS-c3fTch6W96KKHl5Nm6snW2-Z0Tb2TT4_4V1vzjd2WCDdnW531tVg2PrZzbW4bj6L552Hp_tN8gfMsS3Z4zfW4J_Twj3-_gdnN6yQPMzpwmR1W2VH7w68YHCg8W3QXPmx17H7RKN3KQs0SS0-j0W7M9Xz64zGBtSW3LNltp2mbYQtW6685kv2dGskpW6dSBHr4v48mqVlkWbs308NmqW66-LwP4_MDSFW12ZNBC8Jn-WxW550QhM2Q0mFGW76pPfs4qrzpLN2Krf377n-NsW6_HsX245l6RrW6yqqX5800dY9dbHFHC04 )  outlines voluntary procedures to comply with provisions of the AI Act that govern general-purpose models. Companies that follow the guidelines will benefit from simplified compliance, greater legal certainty, and potentially lower administrative costs, according to EU officials. Those that don‚Äôt must comply with the law nonetheless, which may prove more costly. While Microsoft, Mistral, and OpenAI said they would follow the guidelines, Meta declined (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VVXZb24RhTN4W6dx1km3MnbTbW9ccHTJ5znPrVN4xH9fd3prCCW8wLKSR6lZ3q4W9fK9hl5fpLL3W2h0DyX1zPMKsW30xRXc6SJqhqW4RQvY776csZjW57CLhp5vw5ncW8k1bPb5b-pk4W4mQVrK54Mw0YW6SGdj14G1MjJW1SL2Pn2g8JxyW4d-qYM73Qk2FW1l6c2N4CvZ3NW4GB5FB8h7NmdW5R31Hk3G43lmW6ywP9555TQMzW90n18X89DG_2W8zc4zb1cjy3xVNm4gK2b9QqGW4zTWkl7k6YKTW1b6xvL3XGL27W65Jq_B1c_24BW2HKnSY1T5QmZW1TxX0K805ZxsVVtlCL5twfZTV9xSkk6Q6QscW4dMZxh3DczJ2W4kJgMJ7BPCyfW1nV0rB5c1Xl-W6JFvHd8Tq0wkf4v3-Lg04 ) , saying that Europe is ‚Äúheading down the wrong path on AI.‚Äù

How it works: The code focuses on ‚Äúgeneral-purpose AI models‚Äù that are capable of performing a wide range of tasks.

- Stricter rules apply to models that are deemed to pose ‚Äúsystemic risk,‚Äù or ‚Äúa risk that is specific to the high-impact capabilities‚Äù owing to a model‚Äôs reach or clear potential for producing negative effects. Managers of such models must perform continuous assessment and mitigation, including identifying and analyzing systemic risks and evaluating how acceptable they are. They must protect against unauthorized access and insider threats.
- Developers who build models that pose systemic risk must maintain a variety of documentation. They must disclose training data and sources, how they obtained rights to the data, the resulting model‚Äôs properties, their testing methods, and computational resources and energy consumed. They must file updates when they make significant changes or upon request of parties that use the model. They must report mishaps and model misbehavior. They must file a report within 2 days of becoming aware of an event that led to a serious and irreversible disruption of critical infrastructure, 5 days to report a cybersecurity breach, and 10 days a model‚Äôs responsibility for a human death.
- The code doesn‚Äôt mention penalties for noncompliance or violations. Further, the code doesn‚Äôt discuss the cost of compliance except to say that assessing and mitigating systemic risks ‚Äúmerits significant investment of time and resources.‚Äù In 2024, Germany‚Äôs Federal Statistical Office estimated (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VVXZb24RhTN4W6dx1km3MnbTbW9ccHTJ5znPrVN4xH9fx3prCCW95jsWP6lZ3mKTQNTg6_GcNhV127K557qPjMW7y_K6s6GC2mzW6w-Tch7w0qrbW17qNLN1ZHy68W8yd9zG5C3w1pN6v4bXf4LFhSW1Xm44t97TPN_W1w19Kn27RG_BW1ZZJTj3xybtMW8qGxpL2QQ4DhW4JY5Nh34RtlCW4060bg8w7cL1W7Q8sZ93VM1kfW1hq0Qs2yYgbkW3Zg3dP356ccYW7_CgFc6nVZfNW6WWLrT4G6pKHW1F6-JP2_hP6NMxL6p2g5TJHW7hjsbY3wDz9tW7Nqlkk6fyGX5W3bsgL21S-qT3W42yq-48n4LPwW85DHLr36cZvKW4KDs896DJ-86N48-1BB5wJbMN2yLGb_Xzk7lMH-x0tFFMX0W814gXR4p9PkWf5S2GRR04 ) that the cost of compliance for a high-risk system would come to roughly $600,000 to get started and another $100,000 annually.

column2: the notion of systemic risk is misguided. Limiting the inherent risk of AI models is as helpful as limiting the inherent risk of electric motors
column3: which would result only in relatively useless motors. We hope for further revisions in the AI Act that relieve burdens on builders of foundation models
column5: and address practical risks of specific applications rather than theoretical risks of their underlying technology (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VVXZb24RhTN4W6dx1km3MnbTbW9ccHTJ5znPrVN4xH9d25m_5PW69t95C6lZ3p6W2B7BYc6ps7FcVc5KrG6b-srHW2C8z6P7sgh5xW9c2Ggq2HFqGHW87P2Mf8D0PSBW1j42z_3vwpCJW58r-yj1XwC5mW6HWFn02wrysrW1Cm6ZD3vCmF5W9j3xX93nk667W7TDrCD9jqYy6W25G5-r40kcK-W1TJcDV7f5TKcVVlYX492Fk7jW6r4g9C4PFt8QW6BLcWL2xZcsKW7lxshh4JD4ZGW6-sPk67HMJHfW2BfHk71DrspYN3pGhRZX9BmwW4YV59p357B0hW2Tlh-j7Y6yL2W2bHC_s7kSmBDW7nr02b1khRPHVqpR517rqfJLVg85PD9fVsrkW3vrWv16H1-WfW1yM1p394-mcCN2xyX0TnNdB-W6Q-15m5_-12mVbQSJK4dXfTbN8KQrqYdNYrRW3G_Lmk7N34qpW2-s1RS7t30cKW2R35Gc4qgjW4W35lCZD5PCxB_f7glQDg04 ) .

column2: it‚Äôs often more effective to start with a working version and gradually improve it than to generate a solution in one shot. By making small
column3: targeted modifications and keeping only those that perform best under automated evaluation
column4: this iterative process can solve problems that LLMs often can‚Äôt solve directly. Google used this idea in its earlier FunSearch (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VVXZb24RhTN4W6dx1km3MnbTbW9ccHTJ5znPrVN4xH9cM5m_5PW5BWr2F6lZ3nrW2kn_sG5rGrvFVH95Fs515s0TW4pPwpJ2jqKtwW7nhvt91BNQJ5VpwD5J7fXq1QW9fsWXg3J_zz_W6ZsDFq1znkVBW7g_1sv2b-BnZW7Y3T7j1X8prjW7x7zm71bHGBWW7ZMRZL14y8jgN6VZbvS46C5hW88mBT_5W4wkKN2XvX50X95P1N2_qfNKjRrfjW1yZdkC6ltZPDW6hmzpX8_cNn5N8LJMy0B55qXW4zv_jq78bDZ2W5Kfl5G3SKhxKW6wmWfd1q6DvzW5-3rhy7Y0gPNW54347d221vqjW2xjr5B4nQfNpN3yLG9k2CJ7xW41lwrs4fN5ymW7LlkZy7lQMZmW6g-2Kd8cwNqLW4DTqgk92BHxpN82W5g_fLjWnW5zZy893xy-chW1qDfxp4KGdHGW8MJM4B1RxQQ_VdCxS560XWYrf7_NGd404 )

I don't consider myself a particularly talented or smart writer.

‚Ä¢ And the brutal (but liberating) truth you need to hear if you want to be a successful writer

p$ Microsoft Cheats on OpenAI with Anthropic

 * Microsoft just started using Claude for Office features because apparently OpenAI can't make a decent PowerPoint slide. Nothing
   says "strategic partnership" like shopping around for your ex's competitor.

 * The OpenAIbMicrosoft marriage is getting messy. When you're paying Amazon's cloud to use a rival's AI, your "exclusive
   partnership" isn't looking so exclusive. (source)
   [https://www.reuters.com/business/microsoft-use-some-ai-anthropic-shift-openai-information-reports-2025-09-09/?utm_source=galaxy.ai&utm_medium=newsletter]

 * p Works seamlessly on web, iOS, and Android

 * p	 Join millions who have switched to Galaxy.ai [https://galaxy.ai]




p Oracle Becomes the AI Gold Rush's Biggest Pickaxe Seller

 * Oracle's stock exploded 40% after revealing that desperate AI companies are throwing multibbillionbdollar contracts at them for
   cloud computing. OpenAI and xAI are basically begging for GPUs.

 * While everyone fights over who has the smartest AI, Oracle is quietly becoming the arms dealer of the AI war b and getting
   closer to a $1 trillion valuation. (source)
   [https://www.reuters.com/business/oracle-surges-ai-cloud-growth-customers-race-secure-computing-capacity-2025-09-10/?utm_source=galaxy.ai&utm_medium=newsletter]

B


p Apple's AI Strategy: "We'll Figure It Out by 2026"

 * Apple barely mentioned AI at their iPhone event and delayed AI Siri until 2026. Tim Cook's master plan is apparently "let
   Google do the hard work."

 * Apple went from "think different" to "think eventually" in the AI race. (source)
   [https://techcrunch.com/2025/09/09/apples-new-iphone-17-devices-dont-have-an-ai-powered-siri-yet-it-doesnt-matter/?utm_source=galaxy.ai&utm_medium=newsletter]

B


p$+ AlterEgo Reads Your Mind (Literally)

 * This wearable detects jaw muscle signals when you "speak" in your head, letting you control devices telepathically. Privacy
   advocates are screaming internally.

 * We've officially reached the "Black Mirror episode" phase of tech development. (source)
   [https://decrypt.co/338527/near-telepathic-wearable-communicate-silently-devices?utm_source=galaxy.ai&utm_medium=newsletter]

B


p0 Nebius Raises $3B Because Data Centers Are the New Oil Wells

 * AI cloud company Nebius is raising $3b/billion right after landing a $17.4b/billion deal with Microsoft. Apparently, storing AI
   models costs more than some countries' GDP.

 * The real AI race isn't about algorithms b it's about who can afford the astronomical electricity bills. (source)
   [https://www.reuters.com/business/ai-infrastructure-company-nebius-raise-3-billion-2025-09-10/?utm_source=galaxy.ai&utm_medium=newsletter]

B


p'  Mercor Hits $10B Valuation for Teaching AI Basic Human Decency

 * A startup that connects AI labs with human trainers just hit a $10+b/billion valuation with $450b/M in revenue. Turns out
   teaching robots not to be terrible is expensive.

 * Even "superintelligent" AI still needs humans to explain why it shouldn't write bomb recipes or political manifestos. (source)
   [https://techcrunch.com/2025/09/09/sources-ai-training-startup-mercor-eyes-10b-valuation-on-450-million-run-rate/?utm_source=galaxy.ai&utm_medium=newsletter]

B


p; Reflection AI Worth $5.5B for Making GitHub Copilot Look Slow

 * This coding AI startup went from zero to $5.5b/billion in six months. Investors are throwing money at anything that can write
   JavaScript without crying.

 * AI coding tools are the new crypto b everyone's convinced they'll be millionaires until they realize the AI still can't center
   a div. (source)
   [https://www.reuters.com/technology/nvidia-backed-reflection-ai-eyes-55-billion-valuation-ai-runs-hot-ft-reports-2025-09-09/?utm_source=galaxy.ai&utm_medium=newsletter]

B


p% Nvidia Drops "Rubin CPX" Chips for Video Generation

 * Nvidia's new chips are specifically designed for creating videos and writing code. Because apparently regular GPUs aren't
   expensive enough yet.

 * Nvidia is building tomorrow's hardware for today's hype bubble b and somehow it keeps working. (source)
   [https://www.reuters.com/business/nvidia-unveils-ai-chips-video-software-generation-2025-09-09/?utm_source=galaxy.ai&utm_medium=newsletter]

B


p Claude Becomes Your Overqualified Intern

 * Anthropic just taught Claude to create Excel spreadsheets and PowerPoint decks directly in chat. Finally, an AI that can do the
   work you've been avoiding.

 * Claude went from "smart chatbot" to "digital employee that doesn't need health insurance." (source)
   [https://www.anthropic.com/news/create-files?utm_source=galaxy.ai&utm_medium=newsletter]

B


p1 Arm Wants to Put AI in Your Toaster

 * Arm's new "Lumex" chips will run AI directly on your phone without internet. Soon your smartphone will be smarter than you
   offline.

 * Edge AI means your devices can spy on you even when the WibFi is down. Progress! (source)
   [https://www.reuters.com/business/arm-launches-new-generation-mobile-chip-designs-geared-ai-2025-09-10/?utm_source=galaxy.ai&utm_medium=newsletter]

B


p0 RSS Creator Tries to Save the Internet from Copyright Lawsuits

 * Real Simple Licensing wants to help AI companies legally pay for training data. Reddit and Yahoo are already on board because
   lawsuits are expensive.

 * Someone finally realized that stealing the entire internet for AI training might have legal consequences. (source)
   [https://techcrunch.com/2025/09/10/rss-co-creator-launches-new-protocol-for-ai-data-licensing/?utm_source=galaxy.ai&utm_medium=newsletter]

B


p' ExbGooglers Build AI That Remembers Everything You Say

 * TwinMind raised $6M for an app that records your conversations and turns them into searchable notes. It's like having a
   personal NSA agent, but voluntary.

 * Finally, an AI that can remember where you put your keys b and also every embarrassing thing you've ever said. (source)
   [https://techcrunch.com/2025/09/10/ex-google-x-trio-wants-their-ai-to-be-your-second-brain-and-they-just-raised-6m-to-make-it-happen/?utm_source=galaxy.ai&utm_medium=newsletter]

B


p$ AI Tamagotchi Startup Fights Loneliness with Shared Virtual Pets

 * Born raised $15M for Pengu, an AI companion you "cobparent" with friends. Because nothing says healthy relationships like
   jointly raising a digital penguin.

 * We've gone from "AI will replace humans" to "AI will help humans pretend to have friends." (source)
   [https://techcrunch.com/2025/09/10/born-maker-of-virtual-pet-pengu-raises-15m-to-launch-a-new-wave-of-social-ai-companions/?utm_source=galaxy.ai&utm_medium=newsletter]

B


p Anchor Founders Launch AI University in Your Pocket

 * Oboe creates personalized learning courses on any topic using AI. It's like Khan Academy, but with more hallucinations and
   venture capital.

 * Why learn from experts when you can learn from an AI that learned from experts who learned from Wikipedia? (source)
   [https://techcrunch.com/2025/09/10/after-selling-to-spotify-anchors-co-founders-are-back-with-oboe-an-ai-powered-app-for-learning/?utm_source=galaxy.ai&utm_medium=newsletter]

column7: Want to make more $$$ as a ghostwriter?
column9:
There are 3 big mistakes keeping 99% of ghostwriters overworked
and underpaid.

And if you get ahead of them now while you‚Äôre building your
ghostwriting side hustle, you‚Äôll be able to scale your income
faster (and escape your 9 to 5) sooner by solving them.

For context, I‚Äôm talking from experience here‚Äîthese kept me
trapped in a vicious cycle of being underpaid and
underappreciated as a writer for many years.

So today, I‚Äôm going to help you fix them.

Let‚Äôs dive in!

****************************************************
Mistake #1: Trying to write ‚Äúanything‚Äù for ‚Äúanyone.‚Äù
****************************************************

Most ghostwriters think they need to be open to every opportunity
that comes their way. When people ask them what they do, they
reel off a whole range of services:

‚ÄúI do a little bit of everything! I write social media posts for
a few digital marketing brands, landing pages for a SaaS company,
marketing emails for a doctor‚Äôs office, and I run the Instagram
pages for a few fashion influencers.‚Äù

While it sounds like they have a lot of work and clients, this
approach makes it harder to land clients.

This is for two reasons:

* Reason #1: They don‚Äôt know the value they provide. If you
provide everything for everyone, then you aren‚Äôt an expert.
You‚Äôre simply a ‚Äúdoer.‚Äù This means your clients decide how to use
you in their business and choose what they think you‚Äôre worth. In
short, you lose all your pricing power.
‚Äã
* Reason #2: You make it impossible to create efficiencies for
yourself. The more ‚Äúdifferent‚Äù services you provide as a
freelance writer and/or ghostwriter, the higher the switching
cost every time you shift your brain from creating one type of
asset to another, the harder it is for you to master the creation
of one specific asset, and the harder it is for you to create
efficiencies for yourself. This is how you end up overworked and
underpaid.

The solution?

Niching down.

‚ÄãClick here to get my niching down formula (this is how the
internet makes you rich). (
https://click.convertkit-mail.com/4zud96604dfeh532w6msxh6708m77t5/kkhmh2ul0xz7k9sk/aHR0cHM6Ly95b3V0dS5iZS81TEFVZl9idkN2TT9zaT13YW1tQUpLVFN3S1FhTTdq
)‚Äã

(
https://click.convertkit-mail.com/4zud96604dfeh532w6msxh6708m77t5/kkhmh2ul0xz7k9sk/aHR0cHM6Ly95b3V0dS5iZS81TEFVZl9idkN2TT9zaT13YW1tQUpLVFN3S1FhTTdq
)‚Äã

****************************************************
Mistake #2: Treating every client as a blank canvas.
****************************************************

Your goal with your ghostwriting business is to write 1 specific
asset to solve 1 specific problem for 1 specific type of person.

You do not need to reinvent the wheel every time, even if your
client ‚Äúthinks‚Äù they are radically different. The same ‚ÄúEmail
template‚Äù or ‚ÄúX Thread template‚Äù or ‚ÄúLanding Page template‚Äù that
works for a nutritionist can also work for a Silicon Valley CEO,
can also work for a fitness trainer, and can also work for a
sushi restaurant. And you should view this as a good thing.

Nicolas Cole üö¢-->

@Nicolascole77

I have ghostwritten for business founders, executives, and
investors.

‚Ä¢ 300+ industry leaders
‚Ä¢ Thousands of articles
‚Ä¢ Tens of millions of views

I used the same 5 article templates every time:

‚Ä¢ Myths
‚Ä¢ The Future
‚Ä¢ Category POV
‚Ä¢ The Frameworks
‚Ä¢ Mistakes & Lessons (
https://click.convertkit-mail.com/4zud96604dfeh532w6msxh6708m77t5/58hvh8umd63er5a7/aHR0cHM6Ly94LmNvbS9OaWNvbGFzY29sZTc3L3N0YXR1cy8xNzg2NTMxNDE4MzIwODkyMDY2
)
4:0 PM ‚Ä¢ May 3, 2024

1
Retweets
31
Likes

Read 2 replies (
https://click.convertkit-mail.com/4zud96604dfeh532w6msxh6708m77t5/58hvh8umd63er5a7/aHR0cHM6Ly94LmNvbS9OaWNvbGFzY29sZTc3L3N0YXR1cy8xNzg2NTMxNDE4MzIwODkyMDY2
)
‚Äã
Once you have a library of proven templates (because you‚Äôve
practiced on yourself) you can deliver the same outcomes over and
over again without having to start from scratch every time
(saving you tons of time and effort).

*****************************************************************
Mistake #3: Being afraid to do ‚ÄúFree Work‚Äù to get your foot in
the door.
*****************************************************************

So many writers underestimate the ROI of working for free.

There are 3 big reasons you should do it:

* Reason #1: Reduces your risk and accelerates your skills. The
bottleneck to your earning potential isn‚Äôt effort. It‚Äôs hours of
practice. So if you remove the financial barrier in the short
term (even if you‚Äôre just charging $8 / hour) then you can
practice the skills you need to deliver outcomes over and over
again‚Äîthen you can charge higher, premium prices.
‚Äã
* Reason #2: See it as a marketing cost‚Äîwith more upside
potential. Freelancers and solopreneurs spend time doing cold
outreach. They spend time marketing their services with social
media content. Doing Free Work is just another marketing expense
but with more chance of converting into paid work further down
the line.
‚Äã
* Reason #3: Makes it easier for people who aren‚Äôt interested to
give you a chance. If you do the first piece for free, then you
prove you‚Äôre the right person for the job. Then, almost
immediately, you have clients asking for more help which means
you can start to charge whatever you want. For a little bit of
time, you unlock so much upside.

I‚Äôm not exaggerating when I say doing Free Work is how I‚Äôve
become friends with well-connected entrepreneurs and created
millions of dollars of opportunities for myself. To this day, I
still do Free Work (and reap loads of benefits from it.)

Nicolas Cole üö¢-->

@Nicolascole77

Every rich person I know has a ‚ÄúI just started working for free
and then‚Ä¶‚Äù story.

And every broke person I know insists you should never do free
work.

Do with that what you will. (

column7: üëÄ What You Should Be Tracking Instead of Views
column9:
Hey Candace,

Hope you‚Äôve had a good start to the week üôå

We‚Äôve now finished all our quarterly planning so I‚Äôve been back
on the filming train this week - already managed to get two
videos out and it finally feels like I‚Äôm starting to get some
momentum with it which is a relief üòÖ

As I‚Äôve said before, we haven‚Äôt uploaded as many videos as we
planned so far this year, and none of the videos have gone viral.
In fact, over the past month we‚Äôve had quite a few videos perform
quite badly in the first 24hrs - 9 or 10 out of 10 in YouTube
Studio.

One of my team members recently asked if seeing a ‚Äú10/10‚Äù video
in our YouTube Studio made me feel any particular way about the
channel. And to be honest, it never feels great. Despite all the
things I can tell myself about the issues with that ‚Äòout of 10‚Äô
ranking, it‚Äôs still never great to see a 9 or 10 and I still get
the same feeling of elation when I see the fireworks with a 1 out
of 10.

But I always have to remind myself that views aren‚Äôt everything.

When you only obsess over creating viral hits, not only does it
suck the fun out of being a YouTuber, but you‚Äôre also chasing the
wrong metric. Instead, you want to find your North Star ‚≠ê

Let me explain‚Ä¶

I‚Äôve now got over 6 million subscribers, but not every video gets
6 million views. Some of those subscribers are completely
inactive‚Äîthey‚Äôre still subscribed, but they‚Äôre not actually
watching anymore. Others, however, are true fans. Not only do
they watch most of my videos, but they also subscribe to my email
newsletters, follow me over on TikTok and Instagram, and take my
courses. They‚Äôre genuinely interested in my content. ü§ù

So, the real focus of your YouTube channel needs to be delivering
consistent value to these loyal fans. Forget the obsession with
getting huge view counts on every single video, because when you
focus on this, you‚Äôll miss the bigger picture. Instead, you want
better engagement and retention from the right people.

And that‚Äôs why you need a North Star metric‚Äîto measure how many
true fans you actually have, and whether or not that number is
growing over time. üìà

Now this isn‚Äôt an exact science, and I‚Äôve always found it pretty
difficult to find the perfect proxy that feels somewhat legit.
But one metric I do find useful is monthly returning viewers -
this is what mine currently looks like:

‚Äã
Just like a software company tracks weekly active users, this
metric gives me a solid sense of how many viewers are coming back
for more‚Äîand coming back consistently. For me, monthly also feels
like the right cadence.

But that‚Äôs not the full story. The balance between creating
content for existing loyal fans and attracting new audiences is
something every creator struggles with‚Äîmyself included. üëã

For example, I know that my true fans are way more likely to
watch a vlog where I document my life and they get to see
everything I‚Äôm up to these days. But vlogs are pretty much
guaranteed to get fewer views than my usual ‚Äúsit down and talk to
the camera‚Äù content, because most people don‚Äôt even know who I
am.

On the other hand, a new viewer is more likely to click on a
video titled something like, ‚Äú9 Passive Incomes Ideas‚Äù or ‚ÄúHow I
Manage My Time - The Trident Calendar System‚Äù - both of which
attracted large numbers of new viewers to the channel which is
obviously needed if you want to continue to grow consistently
too.

Despite always feeling the pain of 9/10 out of 10s, I‚Äôm
relatively chill about the fact that not every video will be a
banger. Some will go viral, some will totally flop, most will be
somewhere in the middle‚Äîand that‚Äôs fine. The key, as I‚Äôve always
said, is trying to remain consistent.

Building a content strategy that helps grow your audience without
burning out or chasing trends is exactly the type of stuff we
talk about in PTYA (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/p9ugxvrl5nb9h252p3qsqhpnkk733hr/08hwhgu297d2grsp/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYWxpYWJkYWFsLmNvbS9wYXJ0LXRpbWUteW91dHViZXItYWNhZGVteS8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW5vcnRoc3Rhcl9hcHIxNiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9Y3JlYXRvcm5vdGVz
). So if today‚Äôs email resonated with you at all, it‚Äôs definitely
worth checking out - here‚Äôs the link (

) ü§ó

(And remember, if you join you‚Äôll also get access to the PTYA
Community which is thriving at the moment and we‚Äôve got some
exciting guests coming up in May too üëÄ)

Alternatively, if you‚Äôre a complete beginner and you‚Äôre worried
about taking that first step, then you might want to check out
The 7 Video Challenge (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/p9ugxvrl5nb9h252p3qsqhpnkk733hr/vqh3hmuovkpoe9hw/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tLzctdmlkZW8tY2hhbGxlbmdlLz91dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bm9ydGhzdGFyX2FwcjE2JnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1jcmVhdG9ybm5vdGVz

people hit publish on that first video - it‚Äôs a challenge

).

And if you want to keep getting CreatorNotes each week with my
musings and advice on YouTube, that‚Äôs totally fine too, I love

Have a great week and speak to you next Wednesday üëã

Ali xx

Hey friends,

Hope you‚Äôve had a good day so far üôå

We got a great response to my email last week about the prompts
from the quarterly workshop so I thought I‚Äôd share the first
activity that we did as part of that event which is honestly one
of the simplest, but eye-opening, exercises that I do every
couple of months - it‚Äôs called the Wheel of Life.

You might‚Äôve heard me mention it before but, if not, it‚Äôs
essentially an exercise to assess your happiness and satisfaction
across different areas of your life.

Here‚Äôs how it works:

1Ô∏è‚É£ Draw a circle and split it into 3 sections, each representing
health, work, and relationships.

2Ô∏è‚É£ Split these 3 big sections into 3 more sections - so within
health you have physical, mental, and spiritual, within work
you've got mission, money, and growth, and within relationships
you've got family, friends, and romantic.

3Ô∏è‚É£ These are your 9 categories, but I like to add a final one
called joy.

4Ô∏è‚É£ Ask yourself: what number would you rate your satisfaction
with life in each of these domains on a scale of 1 to 10? A 10/10
is "man, I cannot imagine my life being any better in this area"
and 1/10 is "I cannot imagine it being any worse.‚Äù

5Ô∏è‚É£ Plot these scores on your Wheel of Life and you end up with a
radar chart that basically shows you which areas of your life are
going well and which need improving.

This is what mine looked like recently:

‚Äã
Whenever I complete this exercise, I always find it incredibly
valuable because the numbers never lie. When you see ‚Äúoh crap,
I've only got a 6/10 for my friends category," it forces you to
think about why that is and what actions you can take to improve
that score.

So I‚Äôve been a bit antisocial since having a baby, and Izzy and I
haven‚Äôt really put in the effort to organise as much stuff with
friends recently, so that area of my life could definitely do
with some work, alongside my physical health and level of joy.

You can even take the Wheel of Life exercise one step further
(which is something we also did in the workshop) by noting down a
small win that you're proud of for each area.

Because the thing is, you don‚Äôt just want to only focus on the
negative. Even if you do have a low score in some areas, there's
always something you can celebrate and worth acknowledging, which
might just be that fact that you survived work without burning
out for example or called a friend you hadn‚Äôt spoken to in a
while.

For me personally, creating the Lifestyle Business Academy (
https://click.kit-mail1.com/o8u2p8v079tqh6wmez3hvhq4m9rrriohqe49l/z2hgh7ue3gw62vbz/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL2xpZmVzdHlsZS1idXNpbmVzcy1hY2FkZW15P3V0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj13b2xfMjkmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPXByb2R1Y3RpdmVub3Rlcw==
) has re-lit this sort of motivation in my belly in terms of
work, and leaning into this whole online business and financial
freedom thing feels really fun and vibey right now, which is
great.

If you didn't attend the workshop then I'd love for you to take a
few minutes to draw your own Wheel of Life in a notebook or
simply write down your scores, and you can use the worksheet
directly from the Autumn reset here (Google Doc (
https://click.kit-mail1.com/o8u2p8v079tqh6wmez3hvhq4m9rrriohqe49l/p8hehqu4zvx6wwir/aHR0cHM6Ly9kb2NzLmdvb2dsZS5jb20vZG9jdW1lbnQvdS80L2QvMVJjaF9oMGNlZTlBb3dtMUM4ZS1xQnlBeVhtUmM1UldvbEh3bEwtNERvaHcvY29weQ==
) and Notion (
https://click.kit-mail1.com/o8u2p8v079tqh6wmez3hvhq4m9rrriohqe49l/x0hph3uewg32v5ug/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubm90aW9uLnNvL0F1dHVtbi1SZXNldC1Xb3JrYm9vay0yMDI1LTI2ZjFhODhlZTg1YzgwYmFhYThkZTg4MDNlY2I4ZjkwP3B2cz0yMQ==
)).

(You‚Äôll also find prompts to help you align your Life Compass -
the general direction you want to head in life - and set
Quarterly Quests for both work and life, which are two frameworks
we talk about within LifeOS (
https://click.kit-mail1.com/o8u2p8v079tqh6wmez3hvhq4m9rrriohqe49l/kkhmh2unl7mw0ohk/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL2xpZmVvcy8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPXdvbF8yOSZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9cHJvZG5vdGVz
)).

And if you did attend, this is your chance to reflect on how you
feel about your Wheel of Life now, just a few weeks later instead
of just putting it aside and forgetting you ever did it üòÖ

As we spoke about in a recent email, the final 90-100 days of
2025 are a perfect opportunity to make meaningful progress in the
areas that need it most, and while it‚Äôs very easy to look at
these scores and think ‚Äúmeh, I'll work on this in January,‚Äù you
really don‚Äôt just have to wait until the new year.

Hope that was useful, and I‚Äôd love to hear which area you‚Äôre
going to prioritise working on over the next few months - hit
reply and let me know!

Talk soon,

Ali xx

column7: Why Most Creators Quit Too Soon
column9:
Hey Candace,

Hope you‚Äôre having a good day so far.

Last week, I talked about how imposter syndrome often holds
people back from taking that first step but once you‚Äôve got
going, the next challenge is to maintain consistently producing
content and making 1% improvements to your videos, especially if
you‚Äôre struggling to get views or see results early on, so I
wanted to address that in today‚Äôs email.

I certainly felt this way at the start of my YouTube journey.
Just like everyone else, I had no subscribers and zero views to
begin with (everyone starts at zero after all üòÖ) and it then took
me a whole 6 months and 52 videos (because I was posting two each
week) to get 1,000 subscribers. And my channel only got monetised
after posting 85 videos. If anything, I think that‚Äôs probably
quite fast too.

Of course, you might remember that I mentioned Cristiano Ronaldo
hit 20 million subscribers in a single day when he joined YouTube
last year - the epitome of ‚Äúovernight success‚Äù - but for 99.9999%
of creators on YouTube, this doesn‚Äôt happen üòÖ

And it reminds me of a Reel that I created earlier this year
about the Chinese bamboo tree. Why? Well, the interesting thing
about this tree is how it grows in that it does absolutely
nothing above ground during the first four years of its life. You
see no shoots, no leaves - it‚Äôs as if you didn‚Äôt plant the tree
in the first place.

But during this time, it‚Äôs actually building this elaborate root
system underground, and then in the fifth year, something
incredible happens - it grows 80 feet in just six weeks.

And this is how success tends to work on YouTube too.

You put in the work every single day, with every upload, yet you
see no visible results. Your videos aren‚Äôt getting many
impressions and views and you‚Äôre not bringing in many new
subscribers, but then after months, or sometimes even years of
posting consistently, suddenly you hit a breakthrough.

The problem is that most people quit during this period when they
think nothing‚Äôs happening. They stop, or they switch niches, or
choose to do something else entirely, but in reality, all of that
work could be laying the foundations or root system that you just
can‚Äôt see yet but which is fundamental to the eventual success of
the channel.

Returning to my own journey, it took me three years to get my
first one million subscribers and things only started to really
compound at that point. But I knew the first few years were just
about creating content consistently, making 1% improvements over
time, and providing value to my audience with every upload.

Of course, this isn‚Äôt the case for everyone and some people do
get viral success, but ever since we started PTYA (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/o8u2p8v079tqh6r69d5hvhq4wowrriohqe49l/x0hph3ue7qqvggig/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYWxpYWJkYWFsLmNvbS9wYXJ0LXRpbWUteW91dHViZXItYWNhZGVteS8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPWJhbWJvb18xMyZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9Y3JlYXRvcm5vdGVz
) back in 2020, I‚Äôve been consistent in saying that you need to
be committed to publishing a video per week for at least 2 years,
making 1% improvements along the way, to put yourself in the best
position to see growth and results.

And we‚Äôve seen success stories from people within the community
that attest to this. Azul Wells (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/o8u2p8v079tqh6r69d5hvhq4wowrriohqe49l/kkhmh2un9xxkgdck/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cueW91dHViZS5jb20vQEF6dWxXZWxscy92aWRlb3M=
), for example, saw limited results for months before his content
started taking off and he‚Äôs now just under 300k subscribers; or
take Simon Alexander Ong (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/o8u2p8v079tqh6r69d5hvhq4wowrriohqe49l/58hvh8ug966rpnb7/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cueW91dHViZS5jb20vQHNpbW9uYWxleGFuZGVybw==
) and his partner Laurie Wang (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/o8u2p8v079tqh6r69d5hvhq4wowrriohqe49l/25h2h9u3ommkrgf8/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cueW91dHViZS5jb20vbGF1cmlleHdhbmc=
) (who we had as guest speakers back in May), they were both
publishing consistently for a couple of years before they each
had a video which provided that catalyst for growth that‚Äôs taken
them both past 150k subscribers on their respective channels.

Of course, you don‚Äôt have to join PTYA (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/o8u2p8v079tqh6r69d5hvhq4wowrriohqe49l/x0hph3ue7qqvggig/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYWxpYWJkYWFsLmNvbS9wYXJ0LXRpbWUteW91dHViZXItYWNhZGVteS8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPWJhbWJvb18xMyZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9Y3JlYXRvcm5vdGVz
) to see results like this, but a lot of our students find that
the course material and a supportive community behind them makes
growing on YouTube - which definitely takes time - much easier.
In particular, the community is one of the main reasons our
students have enjoyed the course so much. Not only is this a
space to share your wins and collect feedback, but it‚Äôs also the
perfect place to be when you‚Äôre struggling to stay motivated
during those slow-growth periods. (If you‚Äôre ready to join, you
can do so here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/o8u2p8v079tqh6r69d5hvhq4wowrriohqe49l/x0hph3ue7qqvggig/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYWxpYWJkYWFsLmNvbS9wYXJ0LXRpbWUteW91dHViZXItYWNhZGVteS8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPWJhbWJvb18xMyZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9Y3JlYXRvcm5vdGVz
)).

But regardless, if you take only one thing away from this email,
remember that if you‚Äôre working hard but not seeing results,
you‚Äôre definitely not failing - you‚Äôre just building roots üôè

Hopefully that‚Äôs a helpful reframe.

Speak soon!

Ali xx

column7: üö´¬†What NOT To Do If You Want To Grow on YouTube
column9:
Hey Candace,

Hope you‚Äôre having a good week.

Quick note before we start - in case you missed it in LifeNotes,
I just want to let you know about the $1k Challenge which is
launching in just a couple of weeks. This is a brand new, 6-week
cohort that we‚Äôre running throughout August and September aimed
at helping you take a first step on a path to financial freedom.
If you want to find out more and be the first to hear when doors
open in a couple of weeks, you can join the waitlist here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/5qu5ex8krot7hn9eov5a6h9mqg344cnh30xrv/qvh8h8ud0dqm76hg/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL3RoZS0xay1jaGFsbGVuZ2UvP2xtLWdhJTNGdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1jcmVhdG9ybm90ZXMmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPTFrXzk3MjUmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbA==
).

Anyway, on with today‚Äôs CreatorNotes. Now, within these emails, I
usually share all the things I‚Äôve learnt from growing my own
YouTube channel over the past 8+ years. But back in May, just
before Creator Week (which you‚Äôve heard me talk a lot about by
this point üòÖ), we had a great session with partners Simon
Alexander Ong (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/5qu5ex8krot7hn9eov5a6h9mqg344cnh30xrv/3ohphdu3n3v5o3sp/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cueW91dHViZS5jb20vQHNpbW9uYWxleGFuZGVybw==
) and Laurie Wang (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/5qu5ex8krot7hn9eov5a6h9mqg344cnh30xrv/n2hohquvkve986c0/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cueW91dHViZS5jb20vbGF1cmlleHdhbmc=
), who are both alumni of PTYA and each have channels in excess
of 150k subs.

Rather than just focusing on what they did to grow both their own
channels to over 100k subs, they wanted to share some of the
things they didn‚Äôt do (which was Simon‚Äôs clever idea btw), and
their talk was a brilliant reminder that sustainable growth on
YouTube isn‚Äôt about doing everything - instead, it‚Äôs about
prioritising the right things, consistently.

With a daughter of their own and both juggling individual
businesses while growing on YouTube, Simon and Laurie truly
embody the ‚Äúpart-time‚Äù element of PTYA, so I thought it‚Äôd be
helpful to share some of the key things they shared to get to
where they are today.

1Ô∏è‚É£ They weren‚Äôt scared to experiment...but in an intelligent way

At the very start, Simon and Laurie gave themselves permission to
experiment with different video ideas. This is really when you‚Äôve
got the most freedom to explore various topics, figure out what
you enjoy talking about, and see what resonates with your
audience.

As your channel grows, you can then start to narrow down your
focus and think more about the type of content you want to create
long term.

For example, Laurie initially made videos about digital
marketing, drawing upon her professional background at Google.
But over time, she realised that she found more joy in sharing
her own personal stories and life lessons, and didn‚Äôt want to get
stuck down a rabbit hole making videos about something she wasn‚Äôt
truly passionate about.

(If you‚Äôre in that stage of figuring things out for your channel
right now, we‚Äôve actually got a whole module inside PTYA (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/5qu5ex8krot7hn9eov5a6h9mqg344cnh30xrv/48hvh7umnmkd5gfq/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYWxpYWJkYWFsLmNvbS9wYXJ0LXRpbWUteW91dHViZXItYWNhZGVteS8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPXNpbW9ubGF1cmllXzImdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPWNyZWF0b3Jub3Rlcw==
) dedicated to finding your niche, with a bunch of practical
tools and frameworks - you can check out here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/5qu5ex8krot7hn9eov5a6h9mqg344cnh30xrv/48hvh7umnmkd5gfq/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYWxpYWJkYWFsLmNvbS9wYXJ0LXRpbWUteW91dHViZXItYWNhZGVteS8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPXNpbW9ubGF1cmllXzImdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPWNyZWF0b3Jub3Rlcw==
) if that sounds interesting).

2Ô∏è‚É£ They didn‚Äôt overthink their editing

You know me, I‚Äôm a big fan of outsourcing your editing pretty
much from the get go ü´£

But Simon and Laurie still edit their own videos (at least for
now), and that‚Äôs only possible because they keep things very
low-lift. They cut out the pauses, sprinkle in a bit of B-roll
here and there, add some text, and maybe a bit of background
music - that‚Äôs it.

And by keeping their editing process super simple, they‚Äôve been
able to stick to a regular schedule of 2 videos a month without
burning out which is an equally important part of the process -
making sure it‚Äôs sustainable.

3Ô∏è‚É£ They didn‚Äôt obsess over thumbnails

Now, if you‚Äôve been following these emails for the past few
months, you know I care a lot about packaging üòÖ. And I still
think your title and thumbnail are key to your success - Simon
and Laurie didn‚Äôt ignore video packaging altogether, their
approach was just slightly different in that they focused less on
the visual design of their thumbnails and more on their thumbnail
text.

‚Äã

‚Äã
As you can see just by looking at their latest videos, you‚Äôll
notice that all their thumbnails look very similar, apart from
the text. In fact, Simon and Laurie use a technique we've often
used on my channel too, in leveraging the thumbnail text to tease
one of the most intriguing ideas from the video e.g. ‚ÄúThe 1%
Secret‚Äù or ‚ÄúIt‚Äôs Not Sleep‚Äù.

One mistake I see loads of creators make is just repeating the
video title (or part of it) in the thumbnail. Please try to avoid
this if you can - the title and thumbnail should work together
and you‚Äôre wasting prime space if you‚Äôre simply repeating the
same terms in two places.

4Ô∏è‚É£ They didn‚Äôt pretend to know everything

In Laurie‚Äôs own words, she said: ‚Äúdocument, don‚Äôt teach‚Äù. And
this perfectly aligns with my whole philosophy of being a guide
not a guru.

Taking your viewers along for the journey - rather than coming
across as super preachy in your videos - not only makes your
content more relatable and enjoyable to watch, but it also means
you don‚Äôt have to worry about getting things ‚Äúright‚Äù all the
time, because you‚Äôre just sharing what you‚Äôre learning as you go.

This whole idea has really helped me throughout my journey on
YouTube and it's something I still remind myself about when I'm
stuck in overthinking mode over a particular video (which still
happens pretty regularly üòÖ).

5Ô∏è‚É£ They didn‚Äôt do it all alone

And finally, they didn‚Äôt embark on this journey on their own.
Simon and Laurie not only had each other, but as I mentioned
earlier, they both joined PTYA and found incredible value in the
Community.

YouTube can be a lonely journey. Friends, family, work colleagues
probably don‚Äôt want to talk about CTR or AVD and if you‚Äôve got no
one to talk to about your creator struggles or empathise with
your YouTube highs and lows, things can get pretty tough so
having that support can really help.

In fact, connecting with others at a similar stage of the journey
can be hugely motivating, reassuring, and supportive - and it‚Äôs
often mentioned by our students as one of the most valuable parts
of joining PTYA.

Big shoutout to Simon and Laurie for sharing all this stuff so
openly - if you want to see the full talk and all the other
workshops from CreatorWeek plus a bunch more interviews with
creators, you can sign up to PTYA here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/5qu5ex8krot7hn9eov5a6h9mqg344cnh30xrv/48hvh7umnmkd5gfq/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYWxpYWJkYWFsLmNvbS9wYXJ0LXRpbWUteW91dHViZXItYWNhZGVteS8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPXNpbW9ubGF1cmllXzImdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPWNyZWF0b3Jub3Rlcw==
) (fyi - we‚Äôve also recently added payment plans as an option if
you missed that update).

Hope you found this useful - let me know what else you‚Äôd like to
hear in these emails by hitting reply. I‚Äôm really keen to
continue to provide value where I can and would love to hear what
you find useful about these emails and/or what you‚Äôre struggling
with so that we can adjust them to be as helpful as possible.

See you next week!

Ali xx

column7: Why Your Data Pipeline Probably Isn‚Äôt Production-Ready
column9:
View this post on the web at https://seattledataguy.substack.com/p/why-your-data-pipeline-probably-isnt

You‚Äôve done it!
You‚Äôve built your first data pipeline. Maybe you‚Äôre a junior data engineer. Maybe you‚Äôre a data analyst shipping your first pipeline into the wild. Either way, you push it to the repo, cross your fingers, and hope for a quick ‚ÄúLGTM‚Äù from the senior data engineer.
Thirty seconds later: 10 comments. And a slightly horrified senior asking if this thing is even ‚Äúproduction-ready.‚Äù
Production-ready? What does that even mean?
Your data pipeline gets data from Point A to Point B, isn‚Äôt that the whole point?
Well‚Ä¶ not exactly.
In this article, I‚Äôll walk through what production-ready actually looks like when it comes to data pipelines, and how you can design yours to survive review (and future you) with a little less pain.
What Happens When You Need To Re-Run The Pipeline - Backfilling
One term you‚Äôll hear from a lot of data engineers [ https://substack.com/redirect/5b770d35-34f3-4c2e-a8e0-0d5e852264c1?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] is backfilling.
"Backfilling a data pipeline" basically means retroactively loading historical data into an existing table. This usually happens when:
A new data source is added
A system error occurs
Data quality [ https://substack.com/redirect/0450eaf8-d780-4f43-a5dc-1c727549bf7d?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] issues are discovered
New columns need to be added and we aren‚Äôt able to use an update statement
At Facebook, backfilling sometimes meant re-running dozens (and I‚Äôm sure for some people, hundreds) of tables, which could translate to hundreds of partitions. And guess what? It was generally pretty easy to do.
You didn‚Äôt have to stress too much about duplicate data or where you might have issues with a pipeline, because those pipelines were designed to be backfilled.
But many aren‚Äôt.
A lot of pipelines are built to push new data in, with zero thought about what happens if they ever need to be re-run. And that‚Äôs where things get risky:
Duplicate Data: If the pipeline isn‚Äôt idempotent, re-running it can insert duplicate records, skewing analytics and reports.
Data Inconsistency: Merging reprocessed historical data with existing data can lead to conflicting or inconsistent results.
Pipeline Failures: Edge cases or errors might pop up when re-running data the pipeline wasn‚Äôt designed to handle.
Downstream Impact: Inaccurate or duplicated data can disrupt downstream applications, business intelligence tools, and data consumers relying on the integrity of your data.
So how do you avoid this?
You need to pause and actually design your pipeline to handle backfills gracefully, by deleting or replacing old data, versioning datasets properly, and handling pipeline failures intentionally.
A few common approaches to avoid duplicate data:
Deleting prior data by date: Very common with API [ https://substack.com/redirect/355d93ac-c304-49d8-b6e7-5d985035ec27?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] ingests. If you‚Äôre loading data day by day, just delete the data for that day and reload it since many APIs ask for a start end end date to limit how much information you pull.
Using merge statements with a unique ID: Common when loading data via slowly changing dimensions since you can insert new records and update existing ones at the same time.
Store data with the file name: When loading files, store metadata like file names so you can easily delete and reload the exact same file without issues. Most common when using SFTP [ https://substack.com/redirect/85bd8aa2-b041-4663-a6d1-b9b7ed21537f?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ].
Partition data by date and overwrite: One of the simplest and most common strategies, especially at larger tech companies. There are a few ways I‚Äôve seen it implemented. But essentially, every day, you load all the data for an entity into the table with a date stamp. You can read more about it here [ https://substack.com/redirect/959ed183-7ce8-44be-afdb-a7f222d50a0f?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ].
Deleting And Replacing The Old Table - By far the simplest approach is just to delete the old table and completely recreate it. This works when you don‚Äôt have a lot of data and you don‚Äôt need the prior data to calculate future fields. It does pose some issues such as if you need that table to always be available, then deleting it can pose a risk.
Each of these methods has its tradeoffs. The point is that you need to think through what would happen if someone were to re-run this pipeline [ https://substack.com/redirect/74da5349-a631-4f95-a70f-ef1d3e66911c?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]. Whether the data comes from a file, an API, or prior tables, will it create duplicate data? Will it fail because the data doesn‚Äôt exist anymore?
How will you avoid that?
Because at some point, someone will re-run in, probably without thinking through all the edge cases.
That‚Äôs why it‚Äôs your job to think through it now (or, at the very least, leave them a run book).
SeattleDataGuy‚Äôs Newsletter is a reader-supported publication. To receive new posts and support my work, consider becoming a free or paid subscriber.
Breaking Down Your Steps Into Logical Units
Have you ever opened up a SQL file and found‚Ä¶ thousands of lines [ https://substack.com/redirect/16c66b31-bb75-4111-af43-64485292d031?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] staring back at you?
It usually happens when a developer tries to do too much in a single step, subqueries stacked on subqueries, CTEs [ https://substack.com/redirect/8f259316-cde2-433c-b0df-8bcbe249538b?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ], endless case logic, etc. It works until it doesn‚Äôt.
This is one of the first big differences between a pipeline built for quick, one-off analysis and one that‚Äôs actually ready for production. It makes sense, cramming all your logic, data cleanup, and maybe even a little EDA into one massive SQL file or Python notebook can be tempting.
But that quick-and-dirty workflow becomes a nightmare when it‚Äôs time to productionize. 
Refactoring a 3,000-line SQL [ https://substack.com/redirect/5faef048-f5b7-4100-9d41-cc751d82ff12?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] script (that‚Äôs grown organically over months or years) is brutal. Every line, field, and logic was added for some reason, usually to meet a specific use case, and now untangling that logic is like defusing a bomb.
The fix? Modularize your pipeline.
Break your workflow [ https://substack.com/redirect/1fe147d9-f53d-400b-ac4e-5e8d7a18fdeb?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] into smaller, logical steps. Here‚Äôs what that usually looks like in practice:
Usually, there are some natural steps that can (and should) be broken down into their own temporary tables, views, or staging layers. Exactly how you do this will depend on your data size, query complexity, and your team‚Äôs standards.
Avoid duplicate logic. Having the same logic scattered in multiple places is a recipe for mistakes. If something changes, odds are you‚Äôll forget to update every location, and that‚Äôs how bugs creep in.
Breaking down your workflow also comes with other benefits. It makes your pipeline easier to test, debug, and update over time (although it can be more difficult to track).
Unit Tests And Data Quality Checks
You‚Äôve probably heard plenty of people talk about the importance of testing and building in data quality checks. Maybe you‚Äôve even written a few yourself, anomaly checks or category checks  [ https://substack.com/redirect/b0210d13-8e09-4dc3-b818-82fa64ea8e0d?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]to see if something looks off.
But that‚Äôs usually where it stops.
The reality is, across companies, people write SQL scripts‚Ä¶ and never really test them.
Many people run into trouble when it comes to writing unit tests for SQL, either because they don‚Äôt do it at all or because writing tests purely in SQL isn‚Äôt exactly straightforward. There‚Äôs often no easy, built-in library to lean on.
(There are a few options as some tools offer data diffs, and some method of unit tests [ https://substack.com/redirect/856247d1-2266-46f9-ad20-aac39ba9749a?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] so you can ensure the logic changes impact your data set as expected)
Even at Facebook, at the time, all you really got was a box showing what scripts you did run, not a setup for SQL unit tests that automatically triggered every time you made a code change.
This is a key distinction I want to call out, the difference between data quality checks that run inside your pipeline while it‚Äôs running vs. testing the data pipeline [ https://substack.com/redirect/ae1c9b84-1810-4645-a943-6c62b4e26139?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] after changing the logic.
There are tools out there that help with SQL testing, but if you don‚Äôt have one, here‚Äôs the general idea of how to approach it:
Create a test set of data.
Know the expected output of key columns, things like the number of account categories or the total revenue for an accounting report.
Write scripts that test one thing at a time. Keep simple SQL scripts that don‚Äôt have loads of complex logic.
The goal is to avoid hiding your logic inside another 200 lines of SQL, because that‚Äôs where mistakes love to hide.
In a perfect world, someone else on your team would write these scripts for your code. But in reality? It‚Äôs probably going to be you.
(Honestly, this feels like a great feature for Snowflake or Databricks to tackle one day. I‚Äôve seen way too many teams manage this process manually, and I haven‚Äôt seen an amazing solution yet. Happy to be proven wrong).
And, of course, the other types of checks still matter, too, in-pipeline validations, post processing data quality checks, etc. These checks help ensure that if bad data sneaks into your pipeline, you‚Äôll at least know about it, and, in some cases, stop the pipelines from pushing that bad data any further.
What About Monitoring and Logging? 
Now, I‚Äôm putting monitoring, logging, and altering in here, but honestly, this should really be handled by whatever data platform [ https://substack.com/redirect/f2b4f32a-927d-4b43-8bd7-6d8b6eb58ef8?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] you‚Äôre using.
If you don‚Äôt have this built-in, that‚Äôs more of a data engineering or platform problem, not necessarily something you should be rebuilding from scratch in every pipeline.
That said, there are still a couple of things you should absolutely be doing:
Log any key information while your pipeline runs, stuff that‚Äôs useful for debugging and maintenance purposes.
Set up alerts for failure or situations where you need to take manual action.
I can‚Äôt tell you the number of times a good log or clear error message has saved me hours of debugging.
Seriously, future you (or someone else on your team) is going to have to troubleshoot this someday. Don‚Äôt make them dig through a 3,000-line SQL script hunting for clues. Give them logs. Give them context. Give them a chance.
Building For Production
Writing a script that pulls data from point A and pushes it to point B isn‚Äôt where your job ends if you‚Äôre trying to build a reliable, production-ready pipeline.
A good pipeline should also be:
Easy to backfill
Built with quality checks, both before the code goes live and while the pipeline runs
Properly monitored and logged
Broken down into clean, manageable steps
Just shipping a 5,000-line query might technically ‚Äúwork‚Äù, but maintaining, debugging, or scaling is a nightmare.
So, before you hit push on your next pipeline, take a minute and really assess it.
Is this built for today‚Äôs use case, or is it built for the long haul?
As always, thanks for reading.

Articles Worth Reading
There are thousands of new articles posted daily all over the web! I have spent a lot of time sifting through some of these articles as well as TechCrunch and companies tech blog and wanted to share some of my favorites!
Enhancing Personalized CRM Communication with Contextual Bandit Strategies
In the competitive landscape of CRM (Customer Relationship Management), the effectiveness of communications like emails and push notifications is pivotal. Optimizing these communications can significantly enhance user engagement, which is crucial for maintaining customer relationships and driving business growth. At Uber, these communications typically begin with creating content using an email template, which often includes several components: a subject line, pre-header, header, banner, body, and more. Among these, the subject line and pre-header are especially crucial to ‚Äåemail open rates. They‚Äôre often the first elements a customer interacts with and can significantly influence the open rate of an email. To overcome the challenges of static optimization methods like A/B testing, we use a multi-armed bandit approach called contextual bandits.
